reviews.text: An in depth and fascinating step into the Tasmanian convict past, specifically the little discussed female convicts. Their experiences were awful, in some ways worse than their male counterparts. The best way to see the site is by purchasing the combination tour ticket, which gives you site entry, a 45 minute heritage tour (led by an informative guide) and "her story", an interactive performance of the life of "Mary" the convict, and her experiences in the female factory. Interesting, informative and moving, you befriend and explore Mary's life. A must see.

We did both Port Arthur and Cascades, and while everyone raves about Port Arthur (with good reason) Cascades is definitely worth a visit. As they say, it's the only convict site which tells the story of the female convicts. I highly recommend buying a ticket to the tour, as the self-guided brochure only scratches the surface. Our guide was informative and interesting, with lots of little anecdotes about what life was really like in this 'female factory'. It's a small site so you only need an hour, including the tour, to see everything, but well worth it.
Very historic place. Best to do a guided tour so you can appreciate the place more. By yourself you would find it hard to understand the significance of the layout.
Doing both tours was great. The reenactment was the best we have seen. Seeing Port Arthur first then cascades really gives you sense of what happened in that era.

Well done centre showing a harrowing bit of our history. The individual stories and the physical descriptions of the inmates brings a human touch. Sad that so much has been destroyed post prison closure but a great job to reconstruct it. It’s also on the route to the Cascade Brewery and is easily walkable from town.

Do Not miss Port Arthur, this historical and World Heritage site is absolutely amazing.... You really can imagine the bad old days when it was full with convicts, the military force and Free settlers.... 
Make sure you wear comfortable shoes and prepare for at least a full day exploring and finding out about this important part of Australian history.
Highly reccomended

Absolutely awesome! The tour guides are passionate and it really comes through during the tour. From the outside it doesn't look like much, but what lays beneath is a real historic treasure. Definitely better than Port Arthur.

Highly knowledgeable guides who gave great insight into buildings and past lives of those who visited the Penitentiary. They set a great mood for the tour which wasn't tacky or fanciful. Our family greatly enjoyed it and would recommend it to others.
Wonderful place to visit.  Rich in early Tasmania history.  Did the ghost tour and loved it.

We went here on a tour in the evening and it was really cool! And they have a working gallows which you don't see every day. It's very much still mostly intact and you can see what it would've been like at various time thru go arts history.
Food was very good. Service fast and friendly.  Liked the different choices.  Not you same old food. We will go back.

Wait staff was very friendly. When asked what to recommend, she had many ideas. The fried ice cream is everything they say it is... it is very awesome and big! Big enough to share. Only one complaint,  the bathrooms... need another toilet there...
Good homemade pizza. They have lots of other choices on the menu. The restaurant was clean and the service was good. Nice location in historic downtown.
The food was great. And everyone working were great because they were so busy due to concert at Five Flags. Great!!

Third time going here the first time ordered a pork tenderloin it was so hard I couldn't even bite into it nor RIP into it.
Second time pizza nice!!
Ordered out one two of there samples
I opened in store to check for ranch and decided to try a cheese ball soggy. I asked the guy if they were just made?
he asked a couple men then said yes 
I showed him how they look and nothing was done. Took my food and 
That will most definitely be my last time visiting this place.
The Antarctic division in Kingston is a nice place with a great cafe with lovely staff
So interesting Loved The Outside floor Map

Another great experience from down under. Liked the historical exhibited timeline of the evolution of the Tasmania. The models of ship showed remarkable detail. Being an old yacht racer, I always wanted to race the Sydney to Hobart race. One of the worlds classic yacht and dangerous races. They give a great history of this iconic race over the years. A plus was a wonderful scrimshaw exhibit.
Toilet gets a C the soap dispenser wasn't working.

What a great museum! The displays are set out in a nice historical order as you walk through. The employees and volunteers are knowledgeable and friendly. They have a well-stocked gift store, also. We happened to catch the "Shipwrecks" exhibit. The information and artifacts in the exhibit are fascinating.
What a great museum! I saw a lot of new things there, it's interesting! good to go!

Lots to see. Thought it may have had a few more model ships on display.
Still enjoyed it.

Really enjoyed discovering this little museum! Plus, the man at the counter was really friendly and offered a discount rate to both of us!

The museum has a very interesting collection of miniature ships, replicas and remaining items from shipwrecks! It was really fascinating to discover some stories about Tasmanian waters. 

Definitely something to do while in Hobart :)

This is by far the most interesting and amazing museum I have ever visited! The building (or should I say buildings?) itself is incredible. The collection is so diverse it must appeal to all visitors. The few displays that got their own room and can be visited privately or in couples were a unique experience. I find that any visitor in Tasmania should take a day to spend in this museum!

Absolutely amazing ! So so much too see and things too do. Would more than highly recommend for families. Well anyone and everyone. This place is amazing ! The experience is amazing it's so so good. If your in Hobart this is a must do !
One of the best galleries I’ve been to. The art work is so amazing, I think I could have stayed there for days. Awesome venue and definitely will be back. The ferry there is also worth the trip.

The most sophisticated and artistic art gallery that I ever visited. Of course it is full collections of modern arts that are placed beautiful in each section. The Pod helps us to understand about each work and keep us concentrate to the artworks. Bare in mind that there are some sections that are not for children due to adultery contents.

Intriguing and unique, MONA (Museum of Old and New Art) was an experience not to be missed in Hobart for art lovers or others who just want to try something new. I enjoyed the variety of pieces on display, from ancient Egypt to modern creative use of lights, film, and colour. Lunch at the museum cafe was very tasty, and had a beautiful view over the river. I'd consider going another day for dinner! Oh, and the vinyard on sight was pretty and produced a nice drop. Next visit I'll try the cellar door!

Best wildlife sanctuary I’ve ever been to. Staff are very knowledgeable and friendly. The animals are super cute. The guided tour is very informative and you get a chance to take photo with the animals too. We had so much fun there and definitely worth visiting. Highly recommended!

It was a fun and memorable experience to visit the sanctuary and also ethical. They do not receive funding from the government, so all the money they raise is from visitors like us :) There were so many kangaroos here to pet and feed, we spent a big portion of our time just hanging out with them. They even have an animal hospital thing on site where we were able to kind of see an animal get operated on. It was a great experience, would recommend.

This reserve places the well-being of unique wildlife at the top of it's mission. Dedicated staff educate the visitor and provide close interaction with kangaroos and close up observations of Tasmanian Devils, wombats, exotic birds and more. Beautifully located above Hobart, this retreat is a must see.

We were really looking forward to the Bonorong night tour as one of the highlights of our trip to Australia, and wow, we sure weren’t disappointed! Absolutely loved getting to interact with all the animals, and the keeper was knowledgeable, passionate, and patient. Totally worth the money (and then some). We also really support all the good work Bonorong is doing both rescuing animals and contributing towards conservation. Absolutely loved the experience, and would highly recommend it to anyone!

The place is smaller than I thought, and we spent more time than I thought. The staff is very friendly, the kangaroos around the park are an experience worth having (tip: they're lazy as hell). Fred the cockatoo let me pet itself for long minutes (please don't try on your own) and said "Bye" on my way out. Definitely a positive experience.

Nice views on top,roughly a 30 min drive from Hobart but a lot of it is one lane driving so If your stick behind a bus or slow car you can’t do anything about it. Half way up is toilet stop and a small cafe

The wind is very strong in this place as it is in the top of mountain. I can't hardly walk in there but the scenery is very beautiful and the sky is very clear and clean. It is better to take a car to got to top of the mountain because it is very slippery, especially if there are snows. However, the car can't go through if the snow is thick.
So picturesque. Just amazing! Loved the indoor look out :) shame it was so foggy I couldn't see a step in front of me. but did have an amazing view driving up :)

What a view via the top of the mountain. So refreshing and amazing place to be. The God is so great that he's created place like this. The morning sunshine and sunset 🌞 would be awesome and on clear days, Hobart is spectacular from the top to view.
Last few kilometres of the drive are dangerous, narrow winding road with no protection along the edge.  Great view when you get there though.

Fabulous gardens just a short trip out of Hobart!

Incredible grounds with fabulous selection and array of plants and exhibits. The French water sculpture and Japanese Gardens were highlights for me.

It’s the kind of space you could spend hours walking around and taking in all the small details.  Everything from the exhibits, to the coffee to the varying array of plants, just fabulous.

Certainly worth a look in!!!

Beautiful gardens. I never knew there were so many varieties of pine - evergreen trees. Amazing collection. 
Also a fantastic café with amazing. Did I say amazing? Cakes! The other food looked equally good but when you're on holidays you can have cake anytime! Friendly, helpful staff everywhere! Go! Enjoy!

Lovely gardens a reasonable walking distance from the pier area of Hobart. Although not very large, there were an amazing number of small gardens dedicated to specific types of plants or regions.  It has the only arctic plant collection with actual plants from that area in a dedicated building chilled to the right temperature.  The grounds were well kept and staff friendly.  A fantastic free attraction.

Best gardens I've ever been to. Beautiful and varied sections of garden. It was great to show the kids the herb and veggie gardens too. It's all so beautiful, you can really appreciate the hard work that's goes into it every day.

Very picturesque site. Beautiful flowers and displays everywhere. Fairly easy to walk around, and they did have golf carts driving the not so able people around. We were here with a cruise visit, so I'm not this is a regular service of the park.

My 1st visit beautiful auditorium saw
EQUUS brilliant play, my friends said I wouldn't enjoy it but I loved it excellent acting.
One down point when actors were at back of stage it was a job to here what  they were saying and I was only in j5.
Went to The Greatest Shwoman Sing a long. It was lovely being able to go to something there at a reasonable price. Hope they do more of these. Ice creams are pricey though.
Lovely theatre. Seats better than most. Handy restaurants nearby

A great place to experience theatre, good acoustics, friendly staff and a really nice ambiance. 
The seating can be a bit cramped and access along the rows not easy, but the plus side is you can be really close to the stage and even at the rear of the stalls you are closer than in many west end top price seats. 
There is a restaurant and bars for pre-theatre food and drinks in subterranean surroundings (the old vaults), while these places have a great atmosphere they are totally impractical for disabled guests as all involve steps with no lifts  - yes I know the age and style of the building is a limitation but I would think at least one of the areas would be accessible?
Lovely theatre. Disabled access via a lift however the door sticks. Limited female loos so queues during the interval. Drinks and ice creams on the expensive side.

Food was excellent bit of an odd range but works well. For those reading this is actually a coin laundry as well as a cafe like the name describes. The staff were incredibly happy to be there except one moody staff member who was less than friendly to myself and other patrons, this would have been a 5 star review if not for her

Disappointed in the coffee selection. Food cafe with really high prices- doesn't seem to be the highest quality. Eclectic vibe with actual washing machines in the place. A bit of a grunge feel with nothing really special besides the eclectic nature of the place.

Unfortunately, I don't think this place lived up to the hype of previous reviews, and that's what took us there. The staff really weren't overly welcoming or attentive and the food and coffee wasn't great at all. I won't be recommending it to anyone visiting Hobart.

Went here on a Wednesday morning for brunch and was blown away by how big their serving was. I ordered Thom’s Thing and it came with a huge mound of chickpeas, guacamole, tomato, spinach and halloumi on a thick sourdough toast. It was very enjoyable. It’s going to be noisy indoors so don’t go if you are planning to have a nice conversation as you eat.

What a ridiculous place! Went there to get laundry done and have some lunch. We didn't even stay for food because most of the laundry machines and driers were out of order and the one machine that would fit our laundry could only do a warm cycle. But no one there, not one staff member,  was able to tell us how warm that would be and we had delicates as well. 

Stay away if you want to have actual laundry done...

Coffee may seem a bit rich on the first sip but by the end of the cup was pretty satisfied. It's good coffee and its consistently good so far wich is the most important thing. Its a pretty cozy little shop and seems great to hang out for a snack but I normally just get take away coffee so I can't really comment in he food yet.

On a recent visut to Hobart, I enjoyed a couple of superb long black, single origins one made with beans from Honduras, the other Etheopian, matched with a perfect croissant. I was very happy to be back in the very special cafe. Excellent customer service & very comfortable place to read or write.
Great shop offering batch brew, espresso, pour over, pastries, and milk based drinks. Great service, attentive staff, minimalist interior and high quality coffee.

We read some reviews in some blogs and found this place. Didn’t try their coffee but bought a bag for gift.
The staff was friendly and helpful. Gave us some recommendations. Even grind the bean for us.

Tips:
Free 1.5hr parking at nearby Carpark at the Argyle street.
It is a lovely fast paced cafè with a delicious pastry selection and among the best coffee in Hobart. Despite the small available space it never feels crowded or stuffy.

Good ambience. Service is standoffish and experienced that from several waitresses. Food is expensive for what it is. I ordered the admiral's fish pot and was not really impressed. I have had better at cheaper joints. I guess its worth a try.

Excellent establishment. But you should consider making a booking to ensure a table. Oysters for entree were very fresh and we'll presented. Mains of grilled blue eye and the famous seafood chowder were both great. Not cheap but worth it with great staff and good wine list.

Do yourself a favour and get the chowder. It will change your life. One of the best seafood dishes I've ever had. Just amazing. The staff are lovely too. Service was amazing. They are open late ish too which is handy. I was only in Hobart a short while but went back for seconds on that chowder. Highly recommended and will definitely be going back there next time I'm in Hobart. Can get a little busy at peak times though so may want to call to get a table. Good wine and beer list too. Plenty to drink.

I visited Tasmania for a week in 2019 and it started with a trip to this fine restaurant. I have to say that it would have been a perfect trip to Tassie just for the meal. The seafood skewers were amongst the best I've had, the seafood was so fresh. The salmon croquettes were to die for. The staff were extremely friendly and knowledgeable. Couldn't recommend this restaurant more. Well worth the price of admission. Will definitely be back!

Fresh seafood, friendly and efficient service. Servings for the main courses were generous. The meals were on the salty side. Husband thinks it's the stock and sea salt from the seafood. The favourite dish of the day was the fish pot which was a Thai red curry base with seafood and a small serve of rice. It was a very big serve and can be shared with an extra serve of rice. The seafood chowder and skewers were lovely and fresh too.
